 91→
 92→  /* ── Section heading ── */
 93→  .section {
 94→    margin-bottom: 48px;
 95→  }
 96→  .section-title {
 97→    font-size: 11px;
 98→    font-family: var(--mono);
 99→    text-transform: uppercase;
100→    letter-spacing: 2.5px;
101→    color: var(--muted);
102→    margin-bottom: 20px;
103→    display: flex;
104→    align-items: center;
105→    gap: 10px;
106→  }
107→  .section-title::after {
108→    content: '';
109→    flex: 1;
110→    height: 1px;
111→    background: var(--border);
112→  }
113→
114→  /* ── Step card ── */
115→  .step-card {
116→    background: var(--surface);
117→    border: 1px solid var(--border);
118→    border-radius: 8px;
119→    padding: 24px 28px;
120→    margin-bottom: 16px;
121→    position: relative;
122→  }
123→  .step-card::before {
124→    content: attr(data-step);
125→    position: absolute;
126→    top: -1px;
127→    left: -1px;
128→    background: var(--blue);
129→    color: #fff;
130→    font-family: var(--mono);
131→    font-size: 10px;
132→    font-weight: 600;
133→    padding: 3px 10px;
134→    border-radius: 7px 0 6px 0;
135→    letter-spacing: 1px;
136→  }
137→
138→  .step-card h3 {
139→    font-size: 16px;
140→    font-weight: 700;
141→    color: #fff;
142→    margin-bottom: 6px;
143→    margin-top: 10px;
144→  }
145→
146→  /* ── Pill labels ── */
147→  .pill {
148→    display: inline-block;
149→    font-family: var(--mono);
150→    font-size: 10px;
151→    font-weight: 600;
152→    padding: 2px 9px;
153→    border-radius: 99px;
154→    margin-bottom: 14px;
155→    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
156→  }
157→  .pill-obj  { background: var(--blue-dim);   color: var(--blue);   border: 1px solid var(--blue); }
158→  .pill-how  { background: var(--teal-dim);   color: var(--teal);   border: 1px solid var(--teal); }
159→  .pill-why  { background: var(--purple-dim); color: var(--purple); border: 1px solid var(--purple); }
160→  .pill-cmd  { background: var(--amber-dim);  color: var(--amber);  border: 1px solid var(--amber); }
161→
162→  /* ── Subsection inside step ── */
163→  .sub {
164→    margin-top: 16px;
165→    padding-top: 16px;
166→    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
167→  }
168→  .sub-label {
169→    font-family: var(--mono);
170→    font-size: 10px;
171→    font-weight: 600;
172→    letter-spacing: 1.5px;
173→    text-transform: uppercase;
174→    margin-bottom: 8px;
175→  }
176→  .sub-label.obj    { color: var(--blue); }
177→  .sub-label.how    { color: var(--teal); }
178→  .sub-label.why    { color: var(--purple); }
179→
180→  p { margin-bottom: 8px; }
181→  p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
182→
183→  /* ── Code block ── */
184→  .code-block {
185→    background: #080a0e;
186→    border: 1px solid var(--border);
187→    border-left: 3px solid var(--amber);
188→    border-radius: 6px;
189→    padding: 16px 18px;
190→    font-family: var(--mono);
191→    font-size: 12.5px;
192→    line-height: 1.8;
193→    overflow-x: auto;
194→    margin-top: 10px;
195→  }
196→  .code-block .comment { color: var(--muted); }
197→  .code-block .cmd     { color: var(--amber); }
198→  .code-block .arg     { color: var(--teal); }
199→  .code-block .flag    { color: var(--purple); }
200→  .code-block .path    { color: var(--blue); }
201→
202→  /* ── Info / Note box ── */
203→  .note {
204→    background: var(--blue-dim);
205→    border: 1px solid var(--blue);
206→    border-radius: 6px;
207→    padding: 14px 18px;
208→    font-size: 13.5px;
209→    margin-top: 14px;
210→    color: #b8d0ff;
211→  }
212→  .note strong { color: var(--blue); font-family: var(--mono); }
213→
214→  /* ── QnA ── */
215→  .qna {
216→    background: var(--surface);
217→    border: 1px solid var(--border);
218→    border-radius: 8px;
219→    overflow: hidden;
220→    margin-top: 8px;
221→  }
222→  .qna-item {
223→    padding: 14px 20px;
224→    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
225→  }
226→  .qna-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
227→  .qna-q {
228→    font-family: var(--mono);
229→    font-size: 12px;
230→    color: var(--amber);
231→    margin-bottom: 5px;
232→    font-weight: 600;
233→  }
234→  .qna-q::before { content: 'Q  '; opacity: 0.5; }
235→  .qna-a {
236→    font-size: 13.5px;
237→    color: #c5cfe0;
238→    line-height: 1.6;
239→  }
240→  .qna-a::before {
241→    content: 'A  ';
242→    font-family: var(--mono);
243→    font-size: 12px;
244→    color: var(--teal);
245→    font-weight: 600;
246→  }
247→
248→  /* ── Big picture diagram boxes ── */
249→  .flow {
250→    display: flex;
251→    flex-direction: column;
252→    gap: 0;
253→    margin-top: 16px;
254→  }
255→  .flow-item {
256→    display: flex;
257→    align-items: stretch;
258→    gap: 0;
259→  }
260→  .flow-dot {
261→    display: flex;
262→    flex-direction: column;
263→    align-items: center;
264→    width: 40px;
265→    flex-shrink: 0;
266→  }
267→  .flow-dot .dot {
268→    width: 12px;
269→    height: 12px;
270→    border-radius: 50%;
271→    background: var(--blue);
272→    border: 2px solid var(--bg);
273→    margin-top: 6px;
274→    flex-shrink: 0;
275→  }
276→  .flow-dot .line {
277→    width: 2px;
278→    flex: 1;
279→    background: var(--border);
280→    margin-top: 4px;
281→  }
282→  .flow-item:last-child .flow-dot .line { display: none; }
283→  .flow-box {
284→    background: var(--surface);
285→    border: 1px solid var(--border);
286→    border-radius: 6px;
287→    padding: 12px 16px;
288→    margin-bottom: 12px;
289→    flex: 1;
290→  }
291→  .flow-box strong {
292→    color: #fff;
293→    font-size: 14px;
294→  }
295→  .flow-box span {
296→    display: block;
297→    color: var(--muted);
298→    font-size: 12.5px;
299→    font-family: var(--mono);
300→    margin-top: 2px;
301→  }
302→  .flow-box.blue   { border-left: 3px solid var(--blue);   }
303→  .flow-box.teal   { border-left: 3px solid var(--teal);   }
304→  .flow-box.amber  { border-left: 3px solid var(--amber);  }
305→  .flow-box.purple { border-left: 3px solid var(--purple); }
306→  .flow-box.green  { border-left: 3px solid var(--green);  }
307→
308→  /* ── Divider ── */
309→  .divider {
310→    border: none;
311→    border-top: 1px dashed var(--border);
312→    margin: 40px 0;
313→  }
314→
315→  .highlight { color: var(--teal); font-weight: 600; }
316→  .mono-inline {
317→    font-family: var(--mono);
318→    font-size: 12px;
319→    background: #1a1e28;
320→    padding: 1px 6px;
321→    border-radius: 3px;
322→    color: var(--amber);
323→  }
324→</style>
325→</head>
326→<body>
327→<div class="page">
328→
329→  <!-- Header -->
330→  <div class="header">
331→    <div class="tag">Group 9 &nbsp;·&nbsp; Compiler Architecture Assignment</div>
332→    <h1>Custom RISC-V Instruction<br><span>Attention Mechanism (attn)</span></h1>
333→    <p>Modifying the RISC-V GNU Toolchain to add a hardware instruction for Transformer Attention</p>
334→  </div>
335→
336→  <div class="part-label">▸ PART 1 &nbsp;—&nbsp; WHAT, WHY & ENVIRONMENT SETUP</div>
337→
338→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
339→  <!-- SECTION: THE BIG PICTURE -->
340→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
341→  <div class="section">
342→    <div class="section-title">The Big Picture</div>
343→
344→    <div class="step-card" data-step="CONCEPT">
345→      <h3>What exactly did we build?</h3>
346→
347→      <div class="sub">
348→        <div class="sub-label obj">Objective</div>
349→        <p>We added a brand-new CPU instruction called <span class="mono-inline">attn</span> to the RISC-V architecture. This instruction computes the full Transformer Attention formula:</p>
350→        <div class="code-block" style="border-left-color: var(--purple); margin-top:10px; text-align:center; font-size:14px; padding: 18px;">
351→          <span style="color:#fff">Attention(Q, K, V) &nbsp;=&nbsp; Softmax</span><span style="color:var(--teal)">( QKᵀ / √d_k )</span><span style="color:#fff"> · V</span>
352→        </div>
353→        <p style="margin-top:12px">A C program can call this as a single built-in function — <span class="mono-inline">__builtin_riscv_attn(q, k, v)</span> — and the compiler will emit a single <span class="mono-inline">attn</span> instruction in the binary.</p>
354→      </div>
355→
356→      <div class="sub">
357→        <div class="sub-label why">Why build a custom instruction?</div>
358→        <p>On a normal CPU, computing attention requires dozens of instructions: multiply loops, a division, an exponential, normalization, another multiply loop. A <span class="highlight">custom instruction collapses all of that into one opcode</span>. On real custom silicon (like an FPGA or an AI chip), that single instruction would fire dedicated hardware circuits — running in one clock cycle instead of hundreds.</p>
359→        <p>For this assignment, we verify the instruction at the <span class="highlight">compiler level</span>: we prove the compiler knows about it, can emit it, and it shows up correctly in the disassembly.</p>
360→      </div>
361→
362→      <div class="sub">
363→        <div class="sub-label how">How — the three layers we touched</div>
364→        <div class="flow" style="margin-top:12px">
365→          <div class="flow-item">
366→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--blue)"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
367→            <div class="flow-box blue"><strong>riscv-opcodes</strong><span>defines the 32-bit binary encoding of the instruction</span></div>
368→          </div>
369→          <div class="flow-item">
370→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--teal)"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
371→            <div class="flow-box teal"><strong>Binutils (assembler + disassembler)</strong><span>teaches gas to assemble "attn" and objdump to disassemble it</span></div>
372→          </div>
373→          <div class="flow-item">
374→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--purple)"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
375→            <div class="flow-box purple"><strong>GCC (compiler)</strong><span>adds __builtin_riscv_attn so C code can emit the instruction without inline assembly</span></div>
376→          </div>
377→        </div>
378→      </div>
379→    </div>
380→
381→    <!-- QnA -->
382→    <div class="section-title" style="margin-top:28px">Expected Questions</div>
383→    <div class="qna">
384→      <div class="qna-item">
385→        <div class="qna-q">Why not just use inline assembly?</div>
386→        <div class="qna-a">The assignment explicitly forbids it. Also, a built-in is cleaner — it lets GCC optimize register allocation around the instruction.</div>
387→      </div>
388→      <div class="qna-item">
389→        <div class="qna-q">Does the instruction actually execute the math?</div>
390→        <div class="qna-a">At the compiler level (our scope), no. The instruction is emitted and verified via objdump. Actual execution would require a hardware simulator (QEMU) or real chip.</div>
391→      </div>
392→      <div class="qna-item">
393→        <div class="qna-q">What is RISC-V? Why are we modifying its toolchain?</div>
394→        <div class="qna-a">RISC-V is an open-source CPU instruction set. Its toolchain (GCC + Binutils) is open source, making it the standard platform for adding experimental custom instructions.</div>
395→      </div>
396→    </div>
397→  </div>
398→
399→  <hr class="divider"/>
400→
401→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
402→  <!-- STEP 1: INSTALL DEPENDENCIES -->
403→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
404→  <div class="section">
405→    <div class="section-title">Step 1 — Install Dependencies</div>
406→
407→    <div class="step-card" data-step="STEP 01">
408→      <h3>Install all required system libraries</h3>
409→
410→      <div class="sub">
411→        <div class="sub-label obj">Objective</div>
412→        <p>Prepare the Linux/WSL environment with every library needed to compile GCC and Binutils from source.</p>
413→      </div>
414→
415→      <div class="sub">
416→        <div class="sub-label how">Command</div>
417→        <div class="code-block">
418→<span class="cmd">sudo apt-get update</span>
419→<span class="cmd">sudo apt-get install</span> <span class="flag">-y</span> <span class="arg">autoconf automake autotools-dev curl python3 \
420→  libmpc-dev libmpfr-dev libgmp-dev gawk build-essential \
421→  bison flex texinfo gperf libtool patchutils bc \
422→  zlib1g-dev libexpat-dev device-tree-compiler</span>
423→        </div>
424→      </div>
425→
426→      <div class="sub">
427→        <div class="sub-label why">Why each group of packages?</div>
428→        <div class="flow" style="margin-top:10px">
429→          <div class="flow-item">
430→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--amber);width:8px;height:8px;margin-top:8px"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
431→            <div class="flow-box amber"><strong>autoconf, automake, libtool</strong><span>GCC's build system is GNU Autotools — these are required to run ./configure</span></div>
432→          </div>
433→          <div class="flow-item">
434→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--teal);width:8px;height:8px;margin-top:8px"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
435→            <div class="flow-box teal"><strong>libmpc, libmpfr, libgmp</strong><span>GCC needs these math libraries internally to handle arbitrary-precision arithmetic during compilation</span></div>
436→          </div>
437→          <div class="flow-item">
438→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--blue);width:8px;height:8px;margin-top:8px"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
439→            <div class="flow-box blue"><strong>bison, flex</strong><span>Parser generators — GCC's frontend uses them to parse C source code</span></div>
440→          </div>
441→          <div class="flow-item">
442→            <div class="flow-dot"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--purple);width:8px;height:8px;margin-top:8px"></div><div class="line"></div></div>
443→            <div class="flow-box purple"><strong>build-essential, python3</strong><span>Core C/C++ compiler (to compile GCC itself) and Python (used by the riscv-opcodes parser)</span></div>
444→          </div>
445→        </div>
446→      </div>
447→
448→      <div class="note">
449→        <strong>NOTE</strong> &nbsp;This step is identical whether you are on Ubuntu natively or using WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux). Run it once before anything else.
450→      </div>
451→    </div>
452→
453→    <div class="qna">
454→      <div class="qna-item">
455→        <div class="qna-q">Why do we compile GCC from source instead of just downloading it?</div>
456→        <div class="qna-a">We are modifying GCC's internal source files. A pre-built binary won't have our changes. We must compile our patched version ourselves.</div>
457→      </div>
458→      <div class="qna-item">
459→        <div class="qna-q">How long does the build take?</div>
460→        <div class="qna-a">15–40 minutes depending on CPU cores. We use -j$(nproc) to parallelize across all available cores.</div>
461→      </div>
462→    </div>
463→  </div>
464→
465→  <hr class="divider"/>
466→
467→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
468→  <!-- STEP 2: WORKSPACE + CLONE -->
469→  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
470→  <div class="section">
471→    <div class="section-title">Step 2 — Create Workspace & Clone Toolchain</div>
472→
473→    <div class="step-card" data-step="STEP 02">
474→      <h3>Set up folder structure and download the source code</h3>
475→
476→      <div class="sub">
477→        <div class="sub-label obj">Objective</div>
478→        <p>Create a clean working directory and download the RISC-V GNU Toolchain source code along with only the submodules we need (Binutils and GCC).</p>
479→      </div>
480→
481→      <div class="sub">
482→        <div class="sub-label how">Commands</div>
483→        <div class="code-block">
484→<span class="comment"># Create our working directory</span>
485→<span class="cmd">mkdir</span> <span class="flag">-p</span> <span class="path">~/dc</span> <span class="cmd">&amp;&amp; cd</span> <span class="path">~/dc</span>
486→
487→<span class="comment"># Clone the toolchain (--depth 1 = only latest snapshot, saves ~3 GB)</span>
488→<span class="cmd">git clone</span> <span class="flag">--depth 1</span> <span class="arg">https://github.com/riscv-collab/riscv-gnu-toolchain</span>
489→<span class="cmd">cd</span> <span class="path">riscv-gnu-toolchain</span>
490→
491→<span class="comment"># Initialize only binutils and qemu submodules (not all — saves time)</span>
492→<span class="cmd">git submodule update</span> <span class="flag">--init --depth 1</span> <span class="arg">binutils</span>
493→<span class="cmd">git submodule update</span> <span class="flag">--init --depth 1</span> <span class="arg">qemu</span>
494→        </div>
495→      </div>
496→
497→      <div class="sub">
498→        <div class="sub-label why">Why</div>
499→        <p><span class="highlight">--depth 1</span> (shallow clone) downloads only the latest commit, not the entire git history. The full history is several gigabytes — we don't need it since we're patching the current version.</p>
500→        <p>We initialize only the <span class="mono-inline">binutils</span> and <span class="mono-inline">gcc</span> submodules because those are the only ones we modify. The full toolchain has many more submodules (newlib, gdb, etc.) that would take extra time.</p>
501→      </div>
502→    </div>
503→
504→    <!-- Step 3: riscv-opcodes -->
505→    <div class="step-card" data-step="STEP 03" style="margin-top:16px">
506→      <h3>Clone the RISC-V Opcodes tool</h3>
507→
508→      <div class="sub">
509→        <div class="sub-label obj">Objective</div>
510→        <p>Download the official RISC-V opcode definition repository. This is a separate tool used to formally define instruction encodings and auto-generate the <span class="mono-inline">MATCH</span> and <span class="mono-inline">MASK</span> hex constants.</p>
511→      </div>
512→
513→      <div class="sub">
514→        <div class="sub-label how">Command</div>
515→        <div class="code-block">
516→<span class="cmd">cd</span> <span class="path">~/dc</span>
517→<span class="cmd">git clone</span> <span class="flag">--depth 1</span> <span class="arg">https://github.com/riscv/riscv-opcodes</span>
518→        </div>
519→      </div>
520→
521→      <div class="sub">
522→        <div class="sub-label why">Why a separate opcodes repo?</div>
523→        <p>RISC-V instructions are 32-bit words. The layout of bits — which bits are the opcode, which are registers — follows a strict format. The <span class="mono-inline">riscv-opcodes</span> tool lets us <span class="highlight">describe our instruction in human-readable form</span> and automatically computes the correct hex encoding constants. Without it, we'd have to calculate bit fields by hand — error-prone and tedious.</p>
524→      </div>
525→    </div>
526→
527→    <div class="qna">
528→      <div class="qna-item">
529→        <div class="qna-q">What is ~/dc?</div>
530→        <div class="qna-a">"dc" stands for our working directory name. It can be anything — we just use it to keep all our files in one place.</div>
531→      </div>
532→      <div class="qna-item">
533→        <div class="qna-q">Why do we need riscv-opcodes separately? Isn't it inside the toolchain?</div>
534→        <div class="qna-a">The toolchain has its own opcode tables, but riscv-opcodes is the canonical definition tool. We use it to generate correct MATCH/MASK values, then copy those into the toolchain manually.</div>
535→      </div>
536→      <div class="qna-item">
537→        <div class="qna-q">What is a submodule?</div>
538→        <div class="qna-a">A git submodule is a separate git repository embedded inside another. The toolchain repo links to specific versions of binutils, gcc, gdb etc. as submodules.</div>
539→      </div>
540→    </div>
541→  </div>
